Question: Can you follow me back?
What will you do first thing in the morning?

Whenever people post about something bad going on in their lives often a random person will respond with an offer of "DM me if you need to talk"; has anyone ever taken up a stranger for that offer and was it helpful?
Answer: Not ever to just a random person.... When I tell someone that, I mean it, bc I'm an empath...which kinda sucks, but I feel like many others use it as more of an empty gesture, and I'll admit, I can listen well, but I'm not the best problem solver. I have talked to many strangers online before (bc I have no life), and a lot of them either aren't very talkative or good at keeping a conversation going, or [specifically guys] only wanna talk about getting into relationships and/or porn, and want me to get dirty or at least send them lots of pics of myself. Then that just becomes stressful and more depressing.... Plus, I think it's hard to imagine others will understand your problems bc everyone has such different lives. But I think that if you get to know someone for a bit and then start opening up about your problems, it's more likely to be helpful than just spilling everything to a complete stranger. That way, you know them a bit... I've talked a to few people about my problems like that before.....and tbh, only rarely has it been helpful tho....

Question: You've said it beautifully, but I think, however, that you've left out some other important categories - Race, religion, age, social class, for example. No one should be judged for who they love. Love is only wonderful. :)
What do you mean when you say that love is love?
Answer: Well, to me, I would say it means that we love is the same in any instance. We love who we love and that's not our choice bc love is a feeling/sensation that comes from within us; we can't control it.  So, whether it's a girl and guy, girl and girl, or guy and guy, or non-binary and non-binary, or whatever labels,... the love is the same idea; the sexual excitement one gets for anyone is not their choice, it's what their body is naturally reacting to. Because of this, it's unethical for anyone to be telling others who to love and which loving is "right" and which is "wrong," or discriminating against people who don't love who you think they should. Love is just love, there's nothing more to it. It can't hurt nobody, love is not danger, love is not from a rule book.... It's just love. No matter how hard anyone tries to reject a sexual orientation, ignore it, hide from it, abolish it... , it's never gonna change. Love is just love. ❤️

Question: What was the worst shopping experience you’ve ever had?
Answer: It doesn't seem that bad when I say it, but when I was really young, probably like 6 or 7, my family went shopping at Goodwill. The thing we always loved about Goodwill is that everything there was relatively cheap so my parents would let me get more stuff that I wanted. So, on this particular day, we were shopping and we had a cart full of stuff and we were all just kind of in our own aisles picking stuff we wanted while the cart stayed in one aisle that we would go back to when we found something, and put it in. Well, eventually, I guess either it took us all a long time to find whatever or someone was just not doing their job right maybe, idk... But we went back to the aisle at one point and the cart was missing.... so all of our stuff was missing. No one else in my family really minded that much, but I remember that I was really upset bc there was this toy I put in there that I really wanted and then it was gone.... So me for as a child, that was rough haha, and I don't like remembering the sadness I had even tho the situation now just seems dumb

Personally, I don't have very many friends at all so out of desperation, I say yes to pretty much anyone who asks for my number (which is like no one) that doesn't seem like deranged or something. But if I was more picky, the biggest thing for me is probably genuineness. The people I would like to be friends with/get to know better are people who are free from judgment and are very geniune. I find that a lot of people tend to be fairly fake. They act one way around some people and change around others or they lie to please different people....I like people who are just themselves and are loving, accepting and friendly no matter what, not just if you look "pretty" or "handsome/fit the society's social norms or not just if they like exactly what you like or are smart or are a certain race, etc. So I am a lot more likely to want to befriend someone who is like that and someone who I feel like I can relate to in some way so I know we will get along. But ik a lot of other people out there aren't like that -- and some will say they are, but aren't...it's that genuine thing -_-

Question: I believe joy comes from within and being able to  do what really makes you happy will help you a lot.  Also avoid being alone most of the time. Get out n interact with other people n also find something to keep  you busy like joining a gaming club or sports.
Answer: I wish I could do I what would make me happy. I wish I could do that on the world. That's the dream ofc. But life is not like that for me. I try not to be alone but it's not that simple. Not everyone can just exist and then make friends easy. I've tried so hard. I joined clubs, I've pushed myself, I've met people, but in the end they leave me. Everyone else has other friends and don't need me so they don't care. I join things but then I feel left out and they make me feel alone. Other people join with friends so they have someone and then no one talks wants to talk me bc they don't know me. I auditioned for the school drumline but I probably won't even make it in. Life is always like that for me. And even if I did, it turns out I have a scheduling conflict that I may not be able to fix. I tried joining the BSU and went to meetings for over a month, but always felt so isolated and different whenever I was there so I quit. I tried volunteering at a CS class but then there was a scheduling conflict and I had to stop.....I could go on. The point is we can't control our own lives. People tell us that and they think it's true but it's not. Some people just get to be happy while other's either can't be or have to lower their expectations so excessively to the point where being lonely makes you happy.

So I hate being here. And no, you probably can't help. Idk how you could. I've tried to get help, I've pushed myself, I've tried to be what people wanted me to be, I've tried to be what I want to be, but it's just unachievable. So now I just cry and take drugs until hopefully someday I die.

Question: Why does life sucks, I can help you out?
Answer:
So many reasons that would is way too long for an Ask answer to explain. But I'll say a bit.
  
  1. Some people get to be "blessed" or "more blessed" while others have to suffer and barely get by.
  
  2. Some people are born fitting the mythic norm while others don't and are therefore subject to more discrimination, hate, bullying, depression, isolation, feeling unloved by society, etc.
  
  3. You can't be "whatever you want" or "whatever you put your mind to" when you grow up. People tell you that when you're children but the truth is in most of those cases you need to have *a lot* of money and/or be ridiculously smart. Not everyone is like that. Some people take time to learn things, some people have disabilities, some parents don't have great jobs, sometimes life accidents happen that can destroy your future, sometimes people make mistakes they didn't mean to, sometimes people study/work really hard and try their best but they still can't achieve it…..30% of people at most who apply at my University get into the CS program. That's crushing 70% of people's dreams.
  
  4. There's a lot of pressure, especially on young people to do everything right and be the best and accomplish all these achievements.
  
  5. Introverts are less likely to get into programs, schools, jobs, pretty much anything they apply for even though they are not any less capable than extroverts. Being a quiet person is not a defect.
  
  6. Some people have so much hate in them and don't care about dragging others down and destroying them with their words.
  
  7. Discrimination, police brutality, racism, sexism, homophobia, xenophobia, gun violence, massacres….I don't think that needs explanation.
  
  Okay that was a lot and that's just scratching the surface. But point is, I hate life and I want to die. I'm tired of living in this cruel and unforgiving world. I don't get blessed and I never feel happy. I constantly feel lonely, anxious, worried, tired, alone, hurt, not good enough, ugly and most of all, sad.

Okay, well here's some ideas to think about:
  
  For a speech, I would first think about what is something specific you're passionate about? It could be a big issue or topic that's widespread in present time like for example, you're opinion on the discrimination against trans people, or something smaller like perhaps which OS System or phone you think is best.
  
  Then I would think about the goal for the speech. Is it to inform, persuade, educate, to share an opinion...and then think of how something you're passionate about that can work with the goal. And I guess if there isn't any required goal, then think, what aim would you like to have? Or maybe just what seems easiest? Haha.
  
  Then think about the time slot you have and what could fit it best. If it's only 1-2 mins, something smaller/less serious might be the best option. If it's like 5min+, a bigger topic that you could talk more about might be better. Or just something you feel more passionate about over other things.

Why do I want to be popular so bad?
I see people getting 100+ likes on social media or getting very nice comments and it really make me feel left out or not special because I don't even get more than 10 likes on my posts
It just bothers me
How am I supposed to become known or popular?
Answer:
I made an Instagram when I was 13. I introduced it to my bff at the time who made one about 2 wks after me. We followed lots of the same people, but then I noticed people we both knew seemed to only friend request her. Her account started gaining a lot more followers, so I felt left out. I deleted my account later bc it felt embarrassing.
  
  I think what it comes down to is that we need to stop letting social media define us. We feel if we're not getting as many likes on our posts that we're not good enough and it just ends up depressing us, when really we should all love and be proud of ourselves bc we are all just as worthy individuals. Idk how or why some people just receive more love on sm like that, but I try not to worry about it.
  
  I know this wasn't much help, but idk how to get oneself popular. I just know that we shouldn't look down on ourselves bc of some likes on an app. We are special, even when some people fail to acknowledge it online
